Creating new numeric features

Using the cities dataset, create a new feature named city_density by dividing the city population (city_pop) by the city area (city_area). Use the select function to select the city name (name), population, area, and density.

# Question 01
cities |>
  mutate(city_density = city_pop / city_area) |>
  select(name, city_pop, city_area, city_density)

Now, try to summarize the average city density by continent. You should notice that the results include some missing values:

# Question 03
cities |>
  mutate(city_density = city_pop / city_area * 1000) |>
  group_by(continent) |>
  summarize(city_density = mean(city_density))

In the code block below, summarize the average city density by continent again but include the parameter na.rm = TRUE in the mean() function.

# Question 04
cities |>
  mutate(city_density = city_pop / city_area * 1000) |>
  group_by(continent) |>
  summarize(city_density = mean(city_density, na.rm = TRUE))

Now, below, using the mutate verb, create a plot with city density on the x-axis and metro density on the y-axis. Use a log scale for the axes and include points and text repel labels with the city names.

# Question 05
cities |>
  mutate(city_density = city_pop / city_area * 1000) |>
  mutate(metro_density = metro_pop / metro_area * 1000) |>
  ggplot(aes(city_density, metro_density)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_text_repel(aes(label = name)) +
    scale_x_log10() +
    scale_y_log10()

What two outliers stick out in this plot? Answer: Guadalajara and Jinan have a much higher metro density than would be expect based on the city density.

Creating new categorical features

Create a bar plot showing the counts of the the koppen_code feature in the cities dataset. Order the groups categories ordered from the biggest to the smallest. The labels are short so put the categorical variable on the x-axis.

# Question 06
cities |>
  group_by(koppen_code) |>
  summarize(n = n()) |>
  arrange(desc(n)) |>
  mutate(koppen_code = fct_inorder(koppen_code)) |>
  ggplot(aes(koppen_code, n)) +
    geom_col()

In the code below, create a new feature called hemisphere which is equal to â€œNorthâ€ for cities with a latitude above zero and â€œSouthâ€ for cities below zero. Pipe the data to a plot and color the cities by their hemisphere to verify that your code is correct.

# Question 07
cities |>
  mutate(hemisphere = if_else(lat > 0, "North", "South")) |>
  ggplot(aes(lon, lat)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = hemisphere))

Repeat this process below, but this time create a feature called â€œquadrantâ€ that is equal to â€œNEâ€, â€œNWâ€, â€œSEâ€, and â€œSEâ€ depending on the sign of the latitude and longitude features. The easiest way to do this is to start by defining a default value and them fill in the quadrants with four uses of the if_else function. Note: use the & operator to combine two conditions (i.e., (lat > 0) & (lon > 0)).

As above, pipe the data into a plot colored by quadrant to verify your work.

# Question 08
cities |>
  mutate(quadrant = "default") |>
  mutate(quadrant = if_else((lat > 0) & (lon > 0), "NE", quadrant)) |>
  mutate(quadrant = if_else((lat > 0) & (lon < 0), "NW", quadrant)) |>
  mutate(quadrant = if_else((lat < 0) & (lon > 0), "SE", quadrant)) |>
  mutate(quadrant = if_else((lat < 0) & (lon < 0), "SW", quadrant)) |>
  ggplot(aes(lon, lat)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = quadrant))

Grouped Mutate

To conclude, we will apply a few grouped versions of the mutate verb. To make sure we understand how this works, take the us dataset, group by city, and compute the maximum value of the population feature for each city.

# Question 09
us |>
  group_by(city) |>
  mutate(population_max = max(population))

Note that this added a new column to a copy of the original dataset showing the largest population for each city at any point in time.

Building off of this approach, construct a scatter plot that shows the population of cities in 2010 on the x-axis and the percentage of the 2010 population compared to the maximum population of the city from 1790-2010. Filter to only include cities that are less than 70% of their maximum size in 2010. Use a text repel layer to label each city. (Note: This will require at least two different calls to the mutate function).

# Question 10
us |>
  group_by(city) |>
  mutate(population_max = max(population)) |>
  filter(year == 2010) |>
  mutate(percent_pop_max = population / population_max) |>
  filter(percent_pop_max < 0.7) |>
  ggplot(aes(population, percent_pop_max)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_text_repel(aes(label = city))
